Title: Dunstable Downs and Red Kites-12
Description: However; the tip by Jon proved to be 100% correct; and I managed to photograph my first Red Kites today. At the same time I also had a minor education in how farming has changed since I was younger. In my youth I had helped on a couple of harvests; it was hard grueling work; carrying heavy bales by hand and stacking them. Passing them up by hand onto a flat bed trailer. And in those days there were no Red Kites to be seen at all as they have only recently been reintroduced into England. Visit the National Trust Chiltern Gateway Center at www.nationaltrust.org.uk/dunstable-downs-chilterns-gatewa...

Title: Dunstable Downs and Red Kites-10
Description: Then as if to prove a point once the bales had been stacked a Red Kite landed on top of the stack farthest from me! They were getting nearer!

Title: Dunstable Downs and Red Kites-8
Description: It was during the bailing process on the second day that the Red Kites appeared. Soaring high at first; then as the morning went on they became more adventurous and got a little closer.Visit the National Trust Chiltern Gateway Center at www.nationaltrust.org.uk/dunstable-downs-chilterns-gatewa...

Description: The Buckinghamshire and Milton Keynes event to mark Armed Forces Day 2013 took place at the local rugby club ground on the edge of my village yesterday; 29th June; and the sky was alive with all sorts of different planes doing their displays and aerobatics during the afternoon. A lot of them were a bit too far away to see clearly from my garden; but I managed to get a few shots; the best of which are here. The Red Arrows did a fly-by but were so low and fast that I never even got a single shot as they were here and gone so quickly - very impressive sight seeing them so low and in such a tight formation even so.

Red Kite over my garden - 11th June 2013
Description: This wonderful bird appeared over my garden as it was hunting something in a neighbouring garden and was circling around and swooping down occasionally. A wonderful sight; I hesitate to use the overworked word 'awesome' but that best describes it. They appear to be so effortless as they circle around and then they suddenly fold wings close to their body and drop to catch whatever they have sighted. It is a truly wonderful sight and the lowering sun just lit the bird beautifully this time; too often one has to snap away against a light sky and therefore lose the detail as it is shadow; as in some of these shots. I guess that this bird has a wingspan of about five feet.

Title: Red Kite  ---  over my garden
Description: When I find small animals on the roads; I've been bringing them home and leaving them in the grass.I've noticed Red Kites hovering over head; but never caught one coming down to collect the prey. We have a local family of Magpies who have collected several times.I've made several attempts to photograph the hovering Kite; but not had much luck. This is about the best of a bad lot.

Title: Red Kite
Description: For the past year or so; Red Kites have hovered over my garden looking for food. I have never seen them descend to grab the "road kill" I have put out for them -- mainly squirrels or GlisGlis. Nor have I managed to get a decent photo of one at tree top height -- always out of focus and too shaken.They are such magnificent and graceful birds; with a six foot (nearly 2 metres) wingspan. I sometimes get quite near to them in the car; when they come down to collect road kill still on the road. Their eyesight must be remarkable.One day I'll get a good photo. Meanwhile I quite like the light on this one.Some good info and photos on en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_kite

Title: Red Kite - Milvus milvus
Description: This magnificently graceful bird of prey is unmistakable with its reddish-brown body; angled wings and deeply forked tail. It was saved from national extinction by one of the world's longest running protection programmes; and has now been successfully re-introduced to England and Scotland. It is an Amber List species because of its historical decline.Tring. Hertfordshire. June 2014

Title: Red Kite after a scrap!
Description: Scrap can be taken two ways. This bird had clearly been in one as well as looking for some. Wing damage is easy to see but it's talon has also been badly damaged too. A wonderful time watching these beauties in Tetsworth; the Chilterns as a break on the way south. Might be posting a few ....

Title: Red Kite "These feathers do get in the way!"
Description: Got a few shots of a kite landing which is quite unusual for me. Usually they are up there soaring around. It took it some time to rearrange its flight feathers. Quite moth eaten in appearance. I suppose they could be undergoing a moult at the moment?

Title: Red Kite in the Spotlight!
Description: Tetsworth: Bucks. Always have to stop off on our way down south or back. Almost no RKs around. Then this one flies over to see what we were eating! It alighted on the floodlights for the cricket pitch. Just looks like its preening itself in the spotlight; preparing itself for fame!

Title: Day 2 - Flying high 2/365

Title: Red Kite - lighting up a gloomy day! Help to brighten up muddy pics please?
Description: The pics I got are OK but a bit of sun would have helped. I've got several rather muddy shots. If anyone has any suggestions as to how to brighten them up; I would be very grateful to receive messages. Cropped and lightened quite a bit. This bird was quite high in the sky. Had to use a long exposure to get the colour; otherwise the shots were just silhouettes! So they ended up being quite soft around the edges! We often drive down to London on the M40 and see Red Kites in the sky. We decided to take a detour and see if we could see them up close. Thanks to Tim Stenton for giving me a few pointers. A very gloomy day - low cloud cover but the rain held off for most of the time. Well those of you living in ther Chilterns may take these magnificent birds for granted but to us they were just stunning. 300+ pairs since their reintroduction and spreading down into Mid Herts and beyond. I remember whehn the only place theyu could be seen was in Galloway; Scotland.

Title: High as a kite
Description: LARGE is essential !Once almost extinct in the UK; Red Kites (Milvus milvus) were reintroduced in 1989 into various areas including the Chilterns where this one was seen soaring effortlessly hundreds of feet over the Oxfordshire countryside. With their distinctive forked tail and chestnut colouring they are impressive to see and are now gradually increasing in numbers. With a wingspan of up to 2 metres; they are one of the largest birds of prey in the UK.

Driven back from Kent today with a little stop at High Wycombe (technically West Wycombe). We knew from past experience that Red Kites were in the area from being down here before and also seeing them from the M40. What a sight to behold; all those birds instantly recognisable swooping through the air. If you ever have time to spare on the M40; I highly recommend just taking a quick time out and drive through High Wycombe to get the chance to see these wonderful birds. Sue remembers them being reintroduced into the area as shown on Blue Peter about 20-25 years ago and they have thrived in the area.Although I was looking specifically for the viewing point; which I did not find; I did spot this one on top of a lampost

Description: Red Kites hunting over Stokenchurch; Buckinghamshire; just off the M40/A40 junction. A hot sunny Summer day with plenty of rising air is ideal for these birds. These shots were taken with a Canon 200mmm EF lens; not particular good or long; but the birds are hunting down to 15 feet over the roadway. At one point; I had 8 adults in a single frame. In 30 minutes; I saw 25-35 birds; truly remarkable and one of the great wildlife spectacles of Southern England.

Title: Red Kites and the Golden Ball. West Wycombe. Buckinghamshire.
Description: Red kites were driven to extinction in England by human persecution by the end of the nineteenth century. A small population survived in Wales; but there was little chance of these birds repopulating their original areas.Between 1989 and 1994; kites from Spain were imported and released into the Chilterns by the RSPB and English Nature. Red kites started breeding in the Chilterns in 1992 and now there are over 300 breeding pairs in the area.Since 1999; chicks have been taken from the Chilterns to re-introduction sites in other parts of the country.The red kite re-introduction has proved to be one of the greatest conservation success stories of the 20th century.I had been trying all day to get a shot of the dozens of Red Kites that circle over West Wycombe. They are always such a feature of your journey down the M40; but are not so easy to photograph!

Title: A red kite above Hughenden Manor
Description: Hughenden Manor is a red brick Victorian mansion; located in High Wycombe; Buckinghamshire; England. In the 19th century; it was the country house of the Prime Minister; Benjamin Disraeli; 1st Earl of Beaconsfield. Today; it is owned by the National Trust and fully open to the public.The present house was built towards the end of the 18th century and was of a stuccoed and of unassuming design.[4] However; in 1862 the Disraelis had the house remodelled by the architect Edward Buckton Lamb. Lamb has been described as "one of the most perverse and original of mid-Victorian architects".[5] Architecturally; he had a strong interest in the eclectic; this interest is very apparent in his work at Hughenden.Hughenden Manor; the entrance facade.Under Lamb's hand; classical Georgian features were swept away as he "dramatised" the house.[4] Lamb worked in a hybrid baronial form of Gothic architecture; with exposed and angular juxtaposing brickwork surmounted by stepped battlements with diagonal pinnacles. The uppermost windows of the thirteen bayed garden facade were given unusual pediments - appearing almost as machicolations. The architectural historian Nickolaus Pevsner; in his highly critical appraisal of Lamb's work at Hughenden; labels these "window-heads" as "indescribable" and Lamb's overall Hughenden work as "excruciating".[4]Pevsner clearly failed to appreciate what the delighted Disraeli described as the "romance he had been many years realising" while going to say that he imagined it was now "restored to what it was before the civil war".[6] As the house was not originally constructed until the middle of the 18th century; almost a century after the Civil War; that scenario would have been difficult.The house is of three floors. The reception rooms are all on the ground floor; most with large plate glass windows (a Victorian innovation) giving onto the south-facing terrace overlooking a grassy parterre with views over the Hughenden Valley.The west wing was built in 1910; long after Disraeli's death; when the house was in the ownership of his nephew Coningsby Disraeli.en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hughenden_Manor

Title: A red kite with a twig in his beak; nesting in a knoll near Greys Court
Description: The name derives from an old connection to the Grey family; descendants of the Norman knight Anchetil de Greye. The estate or manor of Rotherfield Greys is referred to in the Domesday Book.[2]The mainly Tudor-style house has a courtyard and gardens. The walled gardens contain old-fashioned roses and wisteria; an ornamental vegetable garden; maze (laid to grass with brick paths; dedicated by Archbishop Robert Runcie on 12 October 1981) and ice house. Within its grounds are the fortified tower built circa 1347; the only remains of the medieval castle; overlooking the gardens and surrounding countryside; as well as a Tudor wheelhouse.The house remains furnished as a family home; with some outstanding 18th-century plasterwork interiors.James Paul bought the house in 1688 and it passed via his son William's daughter's dowry to Sir William Stapleton; 4th Baronet in 1724. In 1937 the house was bought from the Stapletons by Sir Felix Brunner and his wife Lady Brunner (ne Elizabeth Irving); the granddaughter of the Victorian actor-manager Sir Henry Irving. In 1969 the family donated the property to the National Trust; where Lady Brunner continued to live until her death in 2003.

Title: At My Fingertips
Description: Olympus OM-1nZuiko 135mmKodak Ektar 100Scanned from negative using Epson Perfection V300.All the photos of these birds were taken on the same day; in the same spot; within about the space of one hour. This is probably my favourite shot. I sat in one spot and they were flying literally 10 feet over my head. The birds pictured are Red Kites; and were re-introduced into my area around 5 years ago. They have grown in numbers and are now an everyday sight. Seeing them at this proximity; however; is not an everyday occurrence and I was extremely lucky to get this many close-up shots on this particular day. The light was absolutely fantastic; as well; which was very fortunate. Perhaps not the most exciting subject for all; but being surrounded (there were a number of different groups of 2 or 3 birds) by birds of prey in such close quarters was quite an exhilarating experience. There were also a few Buzzards flying high above; but they generally soar at much greater altitudes so were more difficult to capture. The picture to the left of this one is an example of a Buzzard in flight; and was about as near as I could get to them on that day.www.tomparkesphoto.com

Title: Red Kite - A heavy heart 503_0254.jpg
Description: It is with a heavy heart that I post 3 images today taken at my golf club on Saturday. I have been a member for 17 years and the club is 111 years old and on 31st March 2021 the flag will be lowered and the doors will be locked for the last time. 5 of the holes will be used to build housing; circa 260 houses; so more green space for wildlife will bite the dust. I went to the course on Saturday for a bit of me time to think about all the wonderful wildlife I have watched there over the years. From Red Kites; Buzzards and Kestrels; to Woodpeckers; Swallows; Thrushes; Pied wagtails; Goldcrest and a variety of tits; as well as Muntjac; Squirrels; Rabbits and much more besides. What will happen to the other 13 holes in time; who knows; I just pray that some will be left for the wonderful variety of wildlife that call this place home for at least part of the year.

Title: Red Kite D61_5544.jpg
Description: An afternoon stroll with the camera looking for Red Kites. Red Kites are distinctive because of their forked tail and striking colour - predominantly chestnut red with white patches under the wings and a pale grey head.They have a wingspan of nearly two metres (about five-and-a-half-feet); but a relatively small body weight of 2 - 3 Ibs.This means the bird is incredibly agile; and can stay in the air for many hours with hardly a beat of its wings.Red Kites are neither particularly strong nor aggressive despite being large birds.Primarily a scavenger and an opportunist; it profits from sheep carrion but is not capable of opening up sheep or lamb carcasses by itself and has to wait until more powerful birds such as ravens or buzzards have made the first inroads before it will attempt to feed.Red Kites are however predators and take a wide variety of live prey; ranging from earthworms to small mammals; amphibians and birds.

Red Kites are distinctive because of their forked tail and striking colour - predominantly chestnut red with white patches under the wings and a pale grey head.They have a wingspan of nearly two metres (about five-and-a-half-feet); but a relatively small body weight of 2 - 3 Ibs.This means the bird is incredibly agile; and can stay in the air for many hours with hardly a beat of its wings.Red Kites are neither particularly strong nor aggressive despite being large birds.Primarily a scavenger and an opportunist; it profits from sheep carrion but is not capable of opening up sheep or lamb carcasses by itself and has to wait until more powerful birds such as ravens or buzzards have made the first inroads before it will attempt to feed.Red Kites are however predators and take a wide variety of live prey; ranging from earthworms to small mammals; amphibians and birds.

Description: 9 June 2011: My daughter's garden; Cox Green; Maidenhead.Like Marsh Harriers at Blacktoft Sands; I keep trying to improve my Red Kite shots when I'm visiting my daughter. I think this is my best so far.The 1;000+ Red Kite population in the Chilterns is going from strength to strength; and they are frequent visitors to urban areas. Two days after I took this photo; I saw 12 birds in the air from my daughter's garden.Must be a lot of carrion in the area!IMG: 2918
